1
00:01:39,350 --> 00:01:44,189
Was that in 1913 or 17?
I can't remember now.

2
00:01:45,523 --> 00:01:50,236
I'm beginning to forget
all the people that I used to know, see?

3
00:01:55,200 --> 00:01:57,785
Do I remember Louise Bryant?

4
00:01:59,412 --> 00:02:02,790
Why, of course.
I couldn't forget her if I tried.

5
00:02:08,213 --> 00:02:09,589
I can't...

6
00:02:09,714 --> 00:02:13,051
I might sort of scratch my memory,

7
00:02:13,134 --> 00:02:15,053
but not at the moment.

8
00:02:16,054 --> 00:02:19,516
You know, things go
and come back again.

9
00:02:20,350 --> 00:02:23,144
It was Christopher Street,

10
00:02:23,728 --> 00:02:26,105
and I was thinking about

11
00:02:26,940 --> 00:02:29,400
another street down there instead,

12
00:02:29,526 --> 00:02:32,946
until it came back
that it was Christopher Street.

13
00:02:33,279 --> 00:02:35,990
Sometimes I have lapses like that.

14
00:02:38,159 --> 00:02:40,245
I'd forgotten all about them.

15
00:02:40,411 --> 00:02:42,247
Were they socialists?

16
00:02:43,748 --> 00:02:45,750
I guess they must've been,

17
00:02:45,834 --> 00:02:47,961
but I don't think they were
of any importance.

18
00:02:48,086 --> 00:02:49,796
I don't remember them at all.

19
00:02:50,129 --> 00:02:53,091
I know that Jack went around
with Mabel Dodge,

20
00:02:53,174 --> 00:02:56,594
and then he went around
with another gal,

21
00:02:56,719 --> 00:02:59,305
and then he went around
with Louise Bryant.

22
00:03:00,515 --> 00:03:02,934
I know there were shifts back and forth,

23
00:03:03,017 --> 00:03:05,478
but it never occurred to me...

24
00:03:05,979 --> 00:03:09,232
It never impinged on
my own personal life.

25
00:03:09,315 --> 00:03:10,608
I like baseball.

26
00:03:10,733 --> 00:03:13,611
I don't know what
the outside world thought of them.

27
00:03:13,945 --> 00:03:15,655
But they were a couple.

28
00:03:16,322 --> 00:03:19,742
I mean, you always spoke of
Louise Bryant and Jack Reed.

29
00:03:19,826 --> 00:03:23,913
I recall his telling me
that he had two ambitions

30
00:03:24,038 --> 00:03:25,498
when he came to college.

31
00:03:25,623 --> 00:03:28,585
One was to be elected
president of his class.

32
00:03:28,668 --> 00:03:31,462
He didn't know anyone in the class.
No one knew him.

33
00:03:31,588 --> 00:03:34,841
The other was to make a million dollars

34
00:03:35,091 --> 00:03:37,010
by the time he was 25.

35
00:03:37,594 --> 00:03:41,931
Now, my idea about Jack Reed
is probably different from most.

36
00:03:42,015 --> 00:03:46,728
But I knew him well.
I knew he was a man of strong views.

37
00:03:46,811 --> 00:03:48,813
I knew he was independent.

38
00:03:48,897 --> 00:03:51,983
And I have an idea,
I may be wrong of this,

39
00:03:52,150 --> 00:03:54,235
that his wife was a Communist

40
00:03:54,736 --> 00:03:58,781
and that his wife had influenced him,
as any wife does,

41
00:03:58,865 --> 00:04:00,450
as you know and I know.

42
00:04:03,203 --> 00:04:04,412
Louise Bryant?

43
00:04:04,495 --> 00:04:08,333
Well, I thought she was something
of an exhibitionist.

44
00:04:08,541 --> 00:04:11,753
No, I'm not gonna talk about people.
Don't fool yourself.

45
00:04:12,253 --> 00:04:16,132
No, sir. I'm not... I'm not

46
00:04:16,883 --> 00:04:18,927
a purveyor of neighborhood gossip,
or anything of the kind.

47
00:04:19,010 --> 00:04:20,178
That's not my job.

48
00:04:20,637 --> 00:04:22,055
He was quiet.

49
00:04:23,598 --> 00:04:25,600
He was a nice fellow.

50
00:04:26,392 --> 00:04:30,480
I would say, if I met him,
I would say he was a nice fellow.

51
00:04:31,523 --> 00:04:34,901
He was, however, a fighting fellow

52
00:04:35,026 --> 00:04:36,903
in regards to principles.

53
00:04:37,028 --> 00:04:41,366
I said, I think,
that a guy who's always interested

54
00:04:41,449 --> 00:04:44,285
in the condition of the world
and changing it

55
00:04:44,369 --> 00:04:46,579
either has no problems of his own

56
00:04:46,788 --> 00:04:48,665
or refuses to face them.

57
00:04:49,082 --> 00:04:52,085
Jack...
Well, I wouldn't call him a playboy,

58
00:04:52,210 --> 00:04:53,503
but some people did.

59
00:04:53,586 --> 00:04:57,632
Jack Reed's life, short as it was,

60
00:04:58,341 --> 00:05:00,093
happened at a time,

61
00:05:00,260 --> 00:05:03,763
and all of us, after all,
are the victims of our time and place,

62
00:05:04,222 --> 00:05:07,725
when he had the opportunity,
as a reporter,

63
00:05:08,017 --> 00:05:11,229
to be in some very exciting
and dramatic places.

64
00:05:11,479 --> 00:05:15,066
It isn't everybody can
be buried in the Kremlin,

65
00:05:15,942 --> 00:05:18,278
and he's the only American.

66
00:05:18,403 --> 00:05:20,864
Born in Portland, Oregon.

67
00:05:22,073 --> 00:05:24,033
Now, isn't that something?

68
00:05:24,534 --> 00:05:26,578
- What's he hugging?
- A statue.

69
00:05:26,703 --> 00:05:29,372
Well, I can see that.
But what's it a statue of?

70
00:05:29,497 --> 00:05:31,082
It's just a statue, Mr. Woodward.

71
00:05:31,207 --> 00:05:33,501
- How much is it?
- It's $75.

72
00:05:33,585 --> 00:05:35,503
- For a photograph?
- That's right, Mrs. Rudisile.

73
00:05:35,587 --> 00:05:37,172
This is interesting, Mrs. Trullinger.

74
00:05:37,297 --> 00:05:39,883
Not that it isn't very nice,
but it isn't a painting.

75
00:05:40,008 --> 00:05:42,218
Mr. Woodward,
I'd like you to look at this.

76
00:05:42,302 --> 00:05:44,387
- I think I see the intention here.
- Yes.

77
00:05:44,470 --> 00:05:46,264
Eve dominates, you see?

78
00:05:46,389 --> 00:05:48,349
The dream dominates the dreamer.

79
00:05:48,600 --> 00:05:49,893
It's...

80
00:05:52,937 --> 00:05:54,731
It looks blurry to me.

81
00:05:54,898 --> 00:05:57,066
The other one looked blurry, too.

82
00:05:57,150 --> 00:06:00,486
I think that's the intention
of the photographer, Mr. Woodward.

83
00:06:00,612 --> 00:06:01,905
What? To be blurry?

84
00:06:02,030 --> 00:06:04,115
But perhaps if you looked at it
from a different point of view...

85
00:06:04,240 --> 00:06:05,408
Louise!

86
00:06:06,159 --> 00:06:07,869
This is you?

87
00:06:14,459 --> 00:06:15,752
Lovely figure.

88
00:06:25,136 --> 00:06:26,763
Louise, have you taken
leave of your senses?

89
00:06:26,846 --> 00:06:28,515
Don't be a fool, Paul.

90
00:06:28,723 --> 00:06:30,558
You think I'm a fool
because I object to my wife

91
00:06:30,642 --> 00:06:32,769
being displayed naked in front
of half the people I know...

92
00:06:32,852 --> 00:06:34,687
Yes. My God,
it's a work of art in a gallery.

93
00:06:34,812 --> 00:06:35,855
What's the matter with you?

94
00:06:35,980 --> 00:06:38,149
You used to call Portland
a stuffy provincial coffin for the mind.

95
00:06:38,274 --> 00:06:39,234
It may be stuffy and provincial,

96
00:06:39,359 --> 00:06:41,402
but it also happens
to be a coffin where I earn a living.

97
00:06:41,486 --> 00:06:43,029
You can take your living
and fill up teeth with it,

98
00:06:43,154 --> 00:06:44,572
because I can earn my own living.

99
00:06:44,656 --> 00:06:45,657
I have my work.

100
00:06:45,782 --> 00:06:49,244
You consider a few articles in
The Oregonian and The Gazette work?

101
00:06:49,327 --> 00:06:50,828
No, I'll tell you
what your work is, Louise.

102
00:06:50,954 --> 00:06:52,956
It's making yourself
the center of attention.

103
00:06:53,039 --> 00:06:56,209
It's shocking Louise Trullinger,
emancipated woman of Portland.

104
00:06:56,334 --> 00:06:58,795
Now, we're gonna say good night
to these people and go home.

105
00:06:58,878 --> 00:07:01,172
- I'm going to the Liberal Club.
- You're not going to the Liberal Club.

106
00:07:01,297 --> 00:07:02,966
- I'm going to the Liberal Club, Paul.
- No, you're not...

107
00:07:04,551 --> 00:07:07,428
It's very nice, Mrs. Trullinger. All of it.

108
00:07:07,804 --> 00:07:10,348
It's very gratifying to hear,
isn't it, Louise?

109
00:07:10,473 --> 00:07:11,891
Isn't it, Louise?

110
00:07:15,144 --> 00:07:18,398
Of course, you know
who is going to be at the Liberal Club.

111
00:07:18,606 --> 00:07:21,192
Patriotic Americans believe in freedom.

112
00:07:21,401 --> 00:07:25,113
And unless we are willing to take arms
to defend our heritage,

113
00:07:25,196 --> 00:07:28,533
we cannot call ourselves
patriotic Americans!

114
00:07:30,076 --> 00:07:31,953
I'm proud to be free.

115
00:07:32,203 --> 00:07:34,038
I'm proud to be an American.

116
00:07:34,163 --> 00:07:36,958
And if the man
we elected President decides

117
00:07:37,041 --> 00:07:38,835
that our freedoms are being threatened

118
00:07:38,960 --> 00:07:41,921
and that the world must
be made safe for democracy,

119
00:07:42,213 --> 00:07:46,509
then I know I won't be alone
in heeding the call of patriotism!

120
00:07:46,718 --> 00:07:48,845
What is this war about?

121
00:07:49,220 --> 00:07:51,598
Each man will have his own answer.

122
00:07:51,973 --> 00:07:55,393
I have mine. I'm ready to be called!

123
00:08:03,693 --> 00:08:05,862
Now, tonight we have with us

124
00:08:05,945 --> 00:08:09,949
the son of Margaret
and the late C.J. Reed of Portland,

125
00:08:10,074 --> 00:08:12,869
who has witnessed this war first-hand.

126
00:08:12,952 --> 00:08:16,331
And I, for one, see no reason
why we here at the Liberal Club

127
00:08:16,414 --> 00:08:19,209
shouldn't listen to what
Jack Reed has to say.

128
00:08:24,631 --> 00:08:28,510
What would you say
this war is about, Jack Reed?

129
00:08:38,811 --> 00:08:40,021
Profits.

130
00:08:41,731 --> 00:08:43,066
What did he say?

131
00:08:48,112 --> 00:08:50,615
Excuse me, Mr. Reed.
Hello, my name is Louise Bryant

132
00:08:50,698 --> 00:08:51,658
and I am a journalist.

133
00:08:51,783 --> 00:08:54,035
And I was wondering if you might
have time to give me an interview.

134
00:08:54,118 --> 00:08:55,328
I'm sorry, I don't. I don't do interviews.

135
00:08:55,453 --> 00:08:57,872
I had a piece in the Blast not long ago.

136
00:08:58,414 --> 00:09:00,750
- Berkman's Blast? Really?
- That's right.

137
00:09:05,255 --> 00:09:06,840
Well, when did you want
to do this interview?

138
00:09:06,965 --> 00:09:07,924
Now.

139
00:09:08,049 --> 00:09:09,175
I don't live here.

140
00:09:09,300 --> 00:09:11,261
- I live in a house by the river.
- Oh, really.

141
00:09:11,386 --> 00:09:13,179
My, my, my. Two places.

142
00:09:15,515 --> 00:09:18,059
Yeah, I use this place as a studio.

143
00:09:19,394 --> 00:09:21,104
Do you like white lilies?

144
00:09:21,771 --> 00:09:23,565
They're my favorite flowers.

145
00:09:24,607 --> 00:09:28,653
- You're not married, are you?
- No, I don't think I believe in marriage.

146
00:09:28,778 --> 00:09:29,737
- Are you married?
- Marriage?

147
00:09:29,863 --> 00:09:31,364
How could anyone believe in marriage?

148
00:09:31,990 --> 00:09:34,742
I bet your mother's glad
to see you back in Portland.

149
00:09:34,826 --> 00:09:37,328
Just glad when I'm not in jail.
Is this you?

150
00:09:37,495 --> 00:09:39,205
Yes. Do you like it?

151
00:09:40,039 --> 00:09:42,375
Yeah. I think they're...

152
00:09:43,168 --> 00:09:47,046
- A little blurry, but this one's very nice.
- Yes.

153
00:09:47,172 --> 00:09:48,298
It is. Now...

154
00:09:50,550 --> 00:09:52,510
Granted, the profit motive
in the world economy

155
00:09:52,635 --> 00:09:54,596
is a basic root cause for the war.

156
00:09:54,679 --> 00:09:56,973
Do you feel that those
Americans who are pro-war

157
00:09:57,098 --> 00:10:00,727
and who ascribe their motives
to patriotism are cynical or naive?

158
00:10:00,852 --> 00:10:03,229
And, if they're cynical,
is it the cynicism of patriots

159
00:10:03,521 --> 00:10:04,981
who feel that without a profit motive,

160
00:10:05,106 --> 00:10:07,817
the power structure elite of this country
will not enter the war,

161
00:10:07,942 --> 00:10:09,360
even though they feel
that the containment

162
00:10:09,444 --> 00:10:11,487
of German militarism
may be necessary for...

163
00:10:11,696 --> 00:10:13,990
All right, Miss Bryant, do you want
an interview? Write this down.

164
00:10:14,073 --> 00:10:15,033
Are you naive enough to think

165
00:10:15,158 --> 00:10:17,493
containing German militarism
has anything to do with this war?

166
00:10:17,577 --> 00:10:20,038
Don't you understand that England
and France own the world economy

167
00:10:20,163 --> 00:10:21,497
and Germany just wants a piece of it?

168
00:10:21,623 --> 00:10:22,665
Keep writing, Miss Bryant.

169
00:10:22,749 --> 00:10:25,001
Miss Bryant, can't you grasp
that J.P. Morgan

170
00:10:25,084 --> 00:10:27,170
has loaned England and France
a billion dollars?

171
00:10:27,253 --> 00:10:29,255
And if Germany wins,
he won't get it back.

172
00:10:29,380 --> 00:10:31,007
More coffee?
America would be entering the war

173
00:10:31,090 --> 00:10:32,300
to protect J.P. Morgan's money.

174
00:10:32,383 --> 00:10:33,593
If he loses it, we'll have a depression.

175
00:10:33,718 --> 00:10:34,844
So, the real question is,

176
00:10:34,928 --> 00:10:37,013
why do we have an economy
where the poor have to pay

177
00:10:37,096 --> 00:10:38,389
so the rich won't lose money?

178
00:10:38,515 --> 00:10:39,891
All right, now, what haven't we covered?

179
00:10:40,016 --> 00:10:42,560
Economic freedom for women
means sexual freedom,

180
00:10:42,685 --> 00:10:44,521
and sexual freedom
means birth control...

181
00:10:44,604 --> 00:10:46,314
Dissent! The Masses stands for dissent.

182
00:10:46,397 --> 00:10:47,690
...we have a predominantly

183
00:10:47,774 --> 00:10:48,942
upper-middle class readership.

184
00:10:49,067 --> 00:10:51,653
So, we have to run around the country
raising money for the magazine

185
00:10:51,736 --> 00:10:53,112
any way we...

186
00:10:57,158 --> 00:10:58,368
What?

187
00:10:59,702 --> 00:11:02,038
Well, I'm thinking that I guess I...

188
00:11:02,247 --> 00:11:04,415
That I ought to offer you more coffee.

189
00:11:04,541 --> 00:11:07,252
I hadn't realized the hour, but

190
00:11:07,669 --> 00:11:10,129
I seem to have taken up
a lot of your time.

191
00:11:10,338 --> 00:11:12,048
Well, that's okay by me.

192
00:11:14,592 --> 00:11:16,469
Does this happen to you often?

193
00:11:17,637 --> 00:11:18,972
Not often enough.

194
00:11:20,431 --> 00:11:21,474
Well?

195
00:11:23,726 --> 00:11:25,395
We certainly have come a long way fast.

196
00:11:25,562 --> 00:11:26,521
Yeah.

197
00:11:27,689 --> 00:11:29,941
Do you want to take it a step further?

198
00:11:30,817 --> 00:11:31,901
Yeah.

199
00:11:34,070 --> 00:11:35,822
What would you think if I asked you
to do something

200
00:11:35,947 --> 00:11:37,991
that might seem a little selfish?

201
00:11:38,366 --> 00:11:40,326
Well, I... I think you should.

202
00:11:40,451 --> 00:11:42,954
Good. Good, because I'd like you
to take a look at my work

203
00:11:43,079 --> 00:11:44,497
and tell me what you think.

204
00:11:44,622 --> 00:11:46,916
You see, I really respect
your opinion so much.

205
00:11:47,041 --> 00:11:49,669
Well, it's odd,
because I was just gonna ask you

206
00:11:49,794 --> 00:11:50,795
if you had anything
I could take a look at.

207
00:11:50,920 --> 00:11:53,256
I know it's an imposition
but I'd be very grateful and you see,

208
00:11:53,339 --> 00:11:55,341
I've read everything
that you've ever written.

209
00:11:55,466 --> 00:11:57,260
Well, I'd be happy to do it. So, that's...

210
00:11:57,427 --> 00:11:58,761
Well, thank you.

211
00:11:59,137 --> 00:12:01,931
Well, then I... I'll get your coat.

212
00:12:03,308 --> 00:12:04,851
Oh, and I hope you won't
be gentle with me.

213
00:12:05,059 --> 00:12:06,519
- Gentle?
- I'm a serious writer.

214
00:12:06,644 --> 00:12:07,604
You can really be tough.

215
00:12:07,729 --> 00:12:09,439
No, I will be. No, I will be.

216
00:12:09,522 --> 00:12:11,107
- Thank you.
- Thank you.

217
00:12:11,566 --> 00:12:14,235
- Do you want me to leave?
- Not really, but I'm late.

218
00:12:14,319 --> 00:12:17,447
- Late at 6:00 in the morning?
- Yes. I have an appointment.

219
00:12:17,780 --> 00:12:19,490
Well, could I see you tomorrow night?

220
00:12:19,616 --> 00:12:20,783
I'm busy tomorrow night.

221
00:12:20,909 --> 00:12:23,286
- Because I'm leaving town the next day.
- Gee, I'm sorry.

222
00:12:23,369 --> 00:12:24,954
So, if you have time,
let me know what you think,

223
00:12:25,038 --> 00:12:27,290
and I'll send you a copy of the interview.

224
00:12:27,707 --> 00:12:29,167
Some interview, huh?

225
00:12:30,710 --> 00:12:32,212
Take a look sometime.

226
00:12:33,421 --> 00:12:36,841
Yeah. Yeah, yeah. Okay, I understand.

227
00:12:36,925 --> 00:12:38,134
- Bye.
- Bye.

228
00:12:47,352 --> 00:12:49,979
Jack, dear,
do you remember Mr. Hardison?

229
00:12:50,104 --> 00:12:53,024
Used to be at the First Presbyterian
Church, up the hill.

230
00:12:53,107 --> 00:12:56,236
He's in Seattle now
at the big Plymouth church.

231
00:13:00,865 --> 00:13:03,326
What brings you out here, Jack?

232
00:13:03,576 --> 00:13:05,870
Just come out to see your mother?

233
00:13:07,872 --> 00:13:12,377
Mr. Partlow, I just... I'm raising money
for this magazine that I write for.

234
00:13:12,502 --> 00:13:14,337
- What?
- I say, I'm raising money

235
00:13:14,462 --> 00:13:16,464
for this magazine that I write for!

236
00:13:16,548 --> 00:13:18,049
- Magazine? What magazine?
- Yes, sir.

237
00:13:18,174 --> 00:13:19,425
Well, it's called The Masses.

238
00:13:19,551 --> 00:13:21,261
- The what?
- The Masses!

239
00:13:21,386 --> 00:13:22,846
- The Masses.
- Masses.

240
00:13:23,221 --> 00:13:26,182
Jack, do you remember
Mr. Potterson's sister?

241
00:13:26,266 --> 00:13:27,600
The one with the bad arm?

242
00:13:27,725 --> 00:13:30,186
- Is that religious?
- Oh, no, sir. No, sir.

243
00:13:30,270 --> 00:13:32,355
Oh, you remember her, Jack.
Her name was Miriam.

244
00:13:32,480 --> 00:13:33,439
She didn't eat meat.

245
00:13:33,565 --> 00:13:35,149
Sounds religious.

246
00:13:35,233 --> 00:13:37,318
You remember the fellow
that was courting her?

247
00:13:37,402 --> 00:13:40,780
Sold spool thread.
Came from down around Eugene.

