00:26:13,491 --> 00:26:14,826
Miss Bryant.

492
00:26:15,493 --> 00:26:17,787
You've been nursing
that beer for an hour.

493
00:26:17,912 --> 00:26:19,497
Can I get you a glass of wine
or something?

494
00:26:19,622 --> 00:26:21,583
No, thank you. I'm fine.
Thank you, anyway.

495
00:26:21,708 --> 00:26:24,335
- Beer's fine.
- You are an amiable person.

496
00:26:24,669 --> 00:26:26,296
And a very good painter, I hear.

497
00:26:27,422 --> 00:26:28,631
I write.

498
00:26:38,725 --> 00:26:40,185
Read Jung!

499
00:26:40,518 --> 00:26:42,896
"Read Freud, read Jung."
Read Engels, read Marx!

500
00:26:43,021 --> 00:26:45,982
My God, you can't interpret Freud
in an economic context.

501
00:26:46,107 --> 00:26:47,942
You know you got a taxi waiting?

502
00:26:48,026 --> 00:26:50,278
Zosima represents
the corruption of religion.

503
00:26:50,361 --> 00:26:51,362
I tell you you're wrong.

504
00:26:51,446 --> 00:26:54,574
- And Jung is a mystic...
- But do you seriously believe...

505
00:26:56,409 --> 00:27:00,371
- How long are they going to stay?
- I don't know. They'll get out in a while.

506
00:27:00,455 --> 00:27:03,499
- I'll only be gone for a day.
- You just got back from Boston.

507
00:27:03,583 --> 00:27:05,001
Hey, why don't you come
with me to Baltimore?

508
00:27:05,084 --> 00:27:07,295
Really? What am I supposed
to come to Baltimore as?

509
00:27:07,378 --> 00:27:08,671
What as?

510
00:27:08,796 --> 00:27:11,132
Jack, you know, you got a taxi waiting.

511
00:27:12,342 --> 00:27:13,801
Taxi's waiting, Jack.

512
00:27:14,886 --> 00:27:16,179
See you tomorrow.

513
00:27:23,895 --> 00:27:26,356
We've been trying for two years.

514
00:27:26,439 --> 00:27:29,734
Capitalists can take this country into
war any time they damn well please.

515
00:27:29,859 --> 00:27:31,986
The only impact you can make
is in the streets.

516
00:27:32,070 --> 00:27:33,112
Of course, but...

517
00:27:33,238 --> 00:27:35,198
But don't you think, Emma,

518
00:27:36,324 --> 00:27:39,035
that if Debs gets a lot of votes,
it'll strengthen that image?

519
00:27:39,118 --> 00:27:41,913
No, I don't. I think voting is the opium
of the masses in this country.

520
00:27:42,038 --> 00:27:43,873
Every four years, you deaden the pain.

521
00:27:43,998 --> 00:27:45,166
Yeah, but...

522
00:27:47,001 --> 00:27:48,127
Don't you think...

523
00:27:48,253 --> 00:27:51,214
I just made it very clear
what I think, Miss Bryant.

524
00:27:51,339 --> 00:27:53,508
Come on, E.G.
Don't be so goddamn dogmatic.

525
00:27:53,591 --> 00:27:56,594
- Louise has a point. She says...
- Suddenly I'm dogmatic.

526
00:27:56,678 --> 00:27:59,597
Why does my status change
every time you get a new woman, Jack?

527
00:27:59,681 --> 00:28:02,892
Bernie, could I have the red wine?
Louise, would you like a glass?

528
00:28:02,976 --> 00:28:04,978
She's just... She's upset with me.

529
00:28:05,103 --> 00:28:07,897
It's got nothing to do with you.
Nothing to do with you.

530
00:28:07,981 --> 00:28:10,650
Thank you. It's a great comfort.

531
00:28:11,025 --> 00:28:13,528
The house is completely filled
with people when you're gone.

532
00:28:13,653 --> 00:28:15,488
They use it as if it was
a meeting hall or something.

533
00:28:15,613 --> 00:28:17,782
- I can't get any work done.
- Just throw them out.

534
00:28:17,907 --> 00:28:19,576
- How am I supposed to throw them out?
- Just kick them out.

535
00:28:19,659 --> 00:28:20,743
Tell them to leave.

536
00:28:20,827 --> 00:28:22,287
I'm not going to
say to Max Eastman, "Leave."

537
00:28:22,370 --> 00:28:23,788
- Just throw them out.
- Jack?

538
00:28:23,913 --> 00:28:26,666
Jack, is that you?
Jack, it's very good to see you.

539
00:28:26,791 --> 00:28:29,252
- Hello, Horace. How are you?
- Very good to see you.

540
00:28:30,670 --> 00:28:33,298
- You know Louise Bryant?
- Yes, hello. How are you?

541
00:28:33,423 --> 00:28:35,425
- Very nice to see you.
- How do you do?

542
00:28:35,550 --> 00:28:36,593
Great pleasure.

543
00:28:36,718 --> 00:28:38,678
- Hi, Max. How are you?
- Divine, Horace.

544
00:28:38,803 --> 00:28:40,597
- And Floyd, good to see you.
- Hello, Horace.

545
00:28:40,805 --> 00:28:42,724
Still getting arrested, Jack?

546
00:28:42,807 --> 00:28:43,933
I try.

547
00:28:46,144 --> 00:28:47,187
How about you, Miss Bryant?

548
00:28:47,312 --> 00:28:49,272
Are you trying to get arrested, too?

549
00:28:49,397 --> 00:28:50,899
No, not really.

550
00:28:52,817 --> 00:28:55,945
- What do you do, Miss Bryant?
- I write.

551
00:28:56,487 --> 00:29:00,533
You write? Now, may I ask,
what are you working on?

552
00:29:02,452 --> 00:29:04,621
It's impossible to describe.

553
00:29:04,746 --> 00:29:06,164
It's impossible to describe?

554
00:29:06,247 --> 00:29:07,248
She just did a hell of a piece

555
00:29:07,373 --> 00:29:09,626
on the influence of the Armory Show
and you ought to read it.

556
00:29:09,709 --> 00:29:11,920
Well, you know,
I very much would like to read that.

557
00:29:12,462 --> 00:29:14,881
Why don't you give me a call
at The Metropolitan?

558
00:29:15,131 --> 00:29:17,926
In fact, even better,
why don't we have a drink on Thursday?

559
00:29:18,009 --> 00:29:20,678
- Fine.
- We can talk about the Armory Show.

560
00:29:20,803 --> 00:29:22,013
- It's a date, then.
- Well, all right.

561
00:29:22,138 --> 00:29:23,598
That's wonderful. Fine.

562
00:29:23,681 --> 00:29:24,933
Jack!

563
00:29:27,852 --> 00:29:30,355
Now, you stay out
of the slammer, now, okay?

564
00:29:32,690 --> 00:29:35,318
Goodbye. Goodbye. Goodbye.
It's nice to see you.

565
00:29:37,362 --> 00:29:39,197
- Jack, please don't do that.
- What?

566
00:29:39,322 --> 00:29:41,449
He's the editor of Metropolitan.
I've known him for years.

567
00:29:41,533 --> 00:29:44,577
- Jack, I can speak for myself.
- So can your work.

568
00:29:44,702 --> 00:29:46,120
- I don't want you to do that...
- Taxi's waiting, Jack.

569
00:29:46,204 --> 00:29:48,164
Oh. Taxi's waiting, Jack.

570
00:29:52,836 --> 00:29:54,003
Jack...

571
00:29:55,255 --> 00:29:57,715
I'll see you at the end
of the week, okay?

572
00:29:59,217 --> 00:30:00,301
- Okay?
- Wait. Wait.

573
00:30:00,385 --> 00:30:02,804
Maybe I will call him about Thursday.

574
00:30:02,887 --> 00:30:05,515
Yeah, call him about Thursday.
Yeah, yeah.

575
00:30:05,640 --> 00:30:07,308
- See you, boys.
- Bye-bye, Jack.

576
00:30:07,392 --> 00:30:09,227
- Bye-bye, Jack.
- See you.

577
00:30:10,061 --> 00:30:11,646
See you, Jack.

578
00:30:17,694 --> 00:30:19,946
"The railroad's opening new frontiers,

579
00:30:20,321 --> 00:30:23,074
"and crisscrossing it all
are the railroads.

580
00:30:23,199 --> 00:30:25,451
"The railroad's opening new frontiers,

581
00:30:25,577 --> 00:30:27,871
"and in turn, these frontiers...

582
00:30:28,162 --> 00:30:30,373
"And in turn, these frontiers..."

583
00:30:30,498 --> 00:30:31,708
Oh, God.

584
00:30:34,794 --> 00:30:36,296
It is repetitious.

585
00:30:40,049 --> 00:30:42,093
We're not human beings,
we're a commodity.

586
00:30:42,218 --> 00:30:43,845
- And how many days a week?
- Seven days.

587
00:30:43,928 --> 00:30:45,054
- Every day?
- They said,

588
00:30:45,180 --> 00:30:48,391
"If you don't come to work on Sunday,
don't come on Monday."

589
00:30:48,516 --> 00:30:50,518
- What do you make an hour?
- 20 cents.

590
00:30:50,602 --> 00:30:53,313
How many times have they
slammed the door on your face

591
00:30:53,438 --> 00:30:55,899
because the labor you do
is called unskilled?

592
00:30:55,982 --> 00:30:57,066
That's right, Bill.

593
00:30:57,192 --> 00:30:59,527
Well, the IWW's not gonna
turn you down

594
00:30:59,611 --> 00:31:01,321
- because you're unskilled.
- Listen to him, George.

595
00:31:01,738 --> 00:31:05,200
Or skilled. Or black or white or yellow.

596
00:31:05,325 --> 00:31:06,576
Seven days a week.

597
00:31:06,701 --> 00:31:08,745
- What do you make an hour?
- 10 cents an hour.

598
00:31:08,828 --> 00:31:09,787
One big union.

599
00:31:10,413 --> 00:31:14,083
- All workers belong...
- Listen, read that. That's important.

600
00:31:14,584 --> 00:31:17,420
I'm looking for a lathe worker
named Pasquale Alberti.

601
00:31:17,504 --> 00:31:20,507
He had an industrial accident. He got
his leg crushed. Do you know him?

602
00:31:20,632 --> 00:31:22,133
Yeah, sure, Harvard.

603
00:31:22,258 --> 00:31:24,677
Is that what they wanna read about
in Greenwich Village now,

604
00:31:24,802 --> 00:31:25,929
industrial accidents?

605
00:31:28,848 --> 00:31:30,725
And for that, we need power.

606
00:31:31,017 --> 00:31:33,603
And there's only one way to get power.

607
00:31:33,937 --> 00:31:35,146
Organize!

608
00:31:35,271 --> 00:31:37,607
All the workers together!

609
00:31:37,732 --> 00:31:39,442
One big union!

610
00:31:39,776 --> 00:31:44,239
And the war the IWW
wants you to get into is class war!

611
00:31:44,322 --> 00:31:46,032
Not a war in Europe!

612
00:31:46,157 --> 00:31:48,284
War against the capitalists!

613
00:31:48,409 --> 00:31:50,787
You'll never get anything or anywhere,

614
00:31:50,912 --> 00:31:54,707
until the whole working class
belongs to one big...

615
00:31:55,333 --> 00:31:57,001
All right, gentlemen,

616
00:31:57,126 --> 00:32:00,004
you've got 20 seconds
to vacate the premises.

617
00:32:07,220 --> 00:32:09,347
May I ask on what authority?

618
00:32:09,472 --> 00:32:11,015
On my authority.

619
00:32:11,224 --> 00:32:13,142
This is an illegal assembly.

620
00:32:13,226 --> 00:32:15,728
Excuse me, Officer. These men
have the legal right to assemble.

621
00:32:15,854 --> 00:32:17,021
That's all they're doing.

622
00:32:17,146 --> 00:32:18,815
We know what the hell they doing.

623
00:32:18,898 --> 00:32:20,817
- What the hell you doing?
- Me?

624
00:32:20,900 --> 00:32:21,985
You.

625
00:32:22,068 --> 00:32:23,528
- I write.
- You write?

626
00:32:24,612 --> 00:32:25,655
You wrong.

627
00:32:29,534 --> 00:32:31,035
Get him out of here!

628
00:32:36,040 --> 00:32:37,417
Here they are.

629
00:32:37,542 --> 00:32:38,710
The folio. The oeuvre.

630
00:32:42,046 --> 00:32:43,214
Well...

631
00:32:44,424 --> 00:32:45,675
How is Jack?

632
00:32:45,800 --> 00:32:49,220
I do hope he's being more careful
about what he's writing these days.

633
00:32:49,345 --> 00:32:51,306
I'd hate to see him not able
to get into print.

634
00:32:51,431 --> 00:32:53,183
Oh, I'm sure he'll do fine.

635
00:32:54,559 --> 00:32:58,062
Did you tell him
where we were having drinks?

636
00:32:58,229 --> 00:33:00,064
No, I will. He's out of town.

637
00:33:00,190 --> 00:33:03,568
Mr. Whigham, excuse me, but
the Armory Show piece is on the top.

638
00:33:03,693 --> 00:33:05,612
Oh, this is the Armory...

639
00:33:05,737 --> 00:33:08,698
- Yes.
- Yes. Of course. Here it is.

640
00:33:15,538 --> 00:33:16,831
Well...

641
00:33:17,624 --> 00:33:19,918
I really ought to spend
more time on this.

642
00:33:20,043 --> 00:33:21,461
Oh, yes, of course.

643
00:33:21,836 --> 00:33:23,171
What about dinner?

644
00:33:24,255 --> 00:33:26,549
- Dinner?
- Jack wouldn't mind.

645
00:33:27,717 --> 00:33:30,553
- Why would he mind?
- Well, we're all grownups, of course,

646
00:33:30,678 --> 00:33:32,555
but Jack's rather...

647
00:33:33,181 --> 00:33:35,016
He's rather an odd duck, isn't he?

648
00:33:35,099 --> 00:33:36,351
And I've never really known how...

649
00:33:36,434 --> 00:33:37,727
Mr. Whigham, are you saying you need

650
00:33:37,810 --> 00:33:40,063
Jack's permission
to make a pass at me?

651
00:33:43,107 --> 00:33:44,234
Don't get so upset about it.

652
00:33:44,317 --> 00:33:46,069
For Christ's sake,
I made two little tiny changes...

653
00:33:46,194 --> 00:33:47,654
Don't rewrite what I write, Pete.

654
00:33:47,779 --> 00:33:49,822
What the hell's the matter
with you, Jack?

655
00:33:49,948 --> 00:33:52,033
The IWW's a bunch of Reds.

656
00:33:52,116 --> 00:33:53,201
Come on.

657
00:33:53,493 --> 00:33:55,787
We got Reds in the IWW,
got Reds in the Village.

658
00:33:55,912 --> 00:33:57,622
We've got nothing
but Reds around here.

659
00:33:57,747 --> 00:34:00,625
For Christ's sake,
you're the best goddamn writer around.

660
00:34:00,750 --> 00:34:02,377
Now, what the hell
you wanna waste your time

661
00:34:02,460 --> 00:34:04,587
with a lot of Red propaganda
nobody's ever gonna print?

662
00:34:04,712 --> 00:34:06,631
It's the truth.
Does that mean anything around here?

663
00:34:06,756 --> 00:34:08,258
Well, who the hell's to say
what the truth is?

664
00:34:08,383 --> 00:34:10,260
A bunch of goddamn Reds in the IWW?

665
00:34:10,343 --> 00:34:12,303
You're not being fair to the AF of L.

666
00:34:12,387 --> 00:34:15,181
- Now, give me the goddamn article...
- You're gonna rewrite what I write.

667
00:34:15,306 --> 00:34:17,392
I'm just gonna take it
to a magazine that won't.

668
00:34:17,475 --> 00:34:19,102
Well, fine. Take it to The Masses.

669
00:34:19,227 --> 00:34:20,520
- They're a bunch of Reds.
- Thank you.

670
00:34:20,645 --> 00:34:22,730
- Who's gonna pay your rent?
- Rent's easy, Pete.

671
00:34:22,814 --> 00:34:25,692
You just don't rewrite what I write.
You got that? Don't rewrite what I write.

672
00:34:25,817 --> 00:34:28,903
You stubborn son of a bitch.
Who's gonna pay your rent?

673
00:34:45,003 --> 00:34:46,129
Louise?

674
00:35:04,230 --> 00:35:06,024
I got every one in the shop.

675
00:35:06,691 --> 00:35:08,693
We're broke, but we've got them all.

676
00:35:12,864 --> 00:35:13,907
Thanks.

677
00:35:18,036 --> 00:35:19,954
- What's the matter?
- Nothing.

678
00:35:20,038 --> 00:35:22,790
- What is it?
- It's nothing. How'd it go?

679
00:35:23,041 --> 00:35:24,667
A lot better than we thought it would.

680
00:35:24,792 --> 00:35:27,629
- You see Whigham?
- Yesterday.

681
00:35:27,712 --> 00:35:30,673
- How was that?
- We mostly talked about you, of course.

682
00:35:30,757 --> 00:35:32,217
Did he offer you work?

683
00:35:32,342 --> 00:35:34,052
No, but he made a big point
of telling me

684
00:35:34,177 --> 00:35:36,763
what wonderful friends
you and he have become over the years.

685
00:35:36,888 --> 00:35:38,765
It was a fascinating meeting.

686
00:35:40,225 --> 00:35:42,185
Are you angry at Whigham or me?

687
00:35:44,812 --> 00:35:45,897
What is it?

688
00:35:46,231 --> 00:35:48,107
It's nothing.
You said you'd be back Tuesday

689
00:35:48,233 --> 00:35:49,442
and it's Saturday.

690
00:35:49,734 --> 00:35:51,486
Didn't I say I'd back
at the end of the week?

691
00:35:51,569 --> 00:35:53,863
- The end of the week is Friday.
- The end of the week is Friday?

692
00:35:53,988 --> 00:35:55,406
Saturday's not the
end of the week anymore, huh?

693
00:35:55,532 --> 00:35:56,908
Jack, you said you'd be back Tuesday!

694
00:35:57,033 --> 00:35:58,076
What difference does it make?

695
00:35:58,201 --> 00:35:59,285
What do you think I've been doing?

696
00:35:59,410 --> 00:36:01,246
Running around listening
to the sound of my own voice?

697
00:36:01,371 --> 00:36:03,331
How do I know whose voice
you've been listening to?

698
00:36:03,414 --> 00:36:05,959
Obviously you like it
a lot better than mine!

699
00:36:16,803 --> 00:36:18,513
Look at me. Oh, God!

700
00:36:19,514 --> 00:36:20,890
I'm like a wife.

701
00:36:22,684 --> 00:36:27,605
I'm like a boring, clinging,
miserable little wife.

702
00:36:28,898 --> 00:36:31,359
- Who'd wanna come home to me?
- Me!

703
00:36:31,943 --> 00:36:33,736
Well, I can't do this!
I can't do this anymore!

704
00:36:33,862 --> 00:36:35,321
You can't do what?

705
00:36:36,614 --> 00:36:38,116
I'm just living in your margins.

706
00:36:38,241 --> 00:36:40,785
I don't know what I'm doing here.
I don't know what my purpose is.

707
00:36:40,910 --> 00:36:44,080
- Well, tell me what you want.
- I want to stop needing you!

708
00:36:44,247 --> 00:36:45,206
I want you to know something.

709
00:36:45,290 --> 00:36:47,750
I asked Whigham
if he'd send me to France.

710
00:36:50,170 --> 00:36:52,672
- Is that what you want?
- That's what I want.

711
00:36:57,051 --> 00:36:59,262
- What are you doing, Louise?
- I can't work around you.

712
00:36:59,345 --> 00:37:00,346
Will you tell me why you're doing this?

713
00:37:00,471 --> 00:37:02,182
I'm not taken seriously
when you're around.

714
00:37:02,307 --> 00:37:03,600
When I'm around
you're not taken seriously?

715
00:37:03,683 --> 00:37:04,851
Oh, God, this is not good.

716
00:37:04,976 --> 00:37:06,352
You mean
you think I'm taken more seriously?

717
00:37:06,477 --> 00:37:07,437
Is that what you're talking about?

718
00:37:07,520 --> 00:37:09,147
Do you mean you're not?
Come on, Jack.

719
00:37:09,272 --> 00:37:11,357
You know what I'm saying.
You're not being honest with me.

720
00:37:11,482 --> 00:37:12,483
I don't know what you're saying.

721
00:37:12,609 --> 00:37:15,153
You're not being honest with me.
Please, be honest with me.

722
00:37:15,278 --> 00:37:16,237
I am so being honest with you.

723
00:37:16,362 --> 00:37:19,115
Maybe if you took yourself a little more
seriously, other people would, too.

724
00:37:19,240 --> 00:37:20,783
I told you what I thought
about the Armory piece.

725
00:37:20,909 --> 00:37:21,910
I was honest about that.

726
00:37:21,993 --> 00:37:24,495
I think it's very nice,
but no, I don't take it very seriously.

727
00:37:24,621 --> 00:37:25,663
- Thank you.
- Why do you even expect

728
00:37:25,788 --> 00:37:28,833
to be taken seriously if you're
not writing about serious things?

729
00:37:28,958 --> 00:37:30,168
I don't understand that.

730
00:37:30,293 --> 00:37:32,420
I found myself an apartment.
I'm looking for one.

731
00:37:32,504 --> 00:37:34,589
I'm not even sure I know
what things you're serious about.

732
00:37:34,672 --> 00:37:35,965
One day you're writing
about the railroads,

733
00:37:36,049 --> 00:37:37,258
and you don't even finish the piece.

734
00:37:37,342 --> 00:37:39,302
The next day you're doing a piece
on an art exhibition

735
00:37:39,385 --> 00:37:40,803
that happened three years ago.

736
00:37:40,929 --> 00:37:42,680
Look, why do you give me
anything to read, anyway?

737
00:37:42,805 --> 00:37:45,225
If I criticize it at all,
you tell me you like it the way it is.

738
00:37:45,350 --> 00:37:46,726
And when we're out with other people,

739
00:37:46,851 --> 00:37:48,603
if somebody doesn't ask you
a direct question,

740
00:37:48,686 --> 00:37:50,021
you tell me you feel ignored.

741
00:37:50,146 --> 00:37:52,148
But with everything
that's happening in the world today,

742
00:37:52,273 --> 00:37:53,900
you decide to sit down and write a piece

743
00:37:54,025 --> 00:37:57,737
on the influence of the goddamned
Armory Show of 1913!

744
00:37:57,862 --> 00:37:59,489
Are people supposed
to take that seriously?

745
00:37:59,614 --> 00:38:00,823
Well, I don't really care!

746
00:38:00,949 --> 00:38:02,325
- You care!
- I'm not really... I don't care!

747
00:38:02,408 --> 00:38:03,952
- You care!
- I don't care!

748
00:38:04,077 --> 00:38:07,121
And I'm not interested
in whether your stupid friends

749
00:38:07,247 --> 00:38:09,415
- take me seriously or not!
- Well, they don't take it seriously.

750
00:38:09,541 --> 00:38:10,708
That's why they don't take it seriously.

751
00:38:10,834 --> 00:38:12,919
I found an apartment on Houston Street,
and I'm moving in.

752
00:38:13,044 --> 00:38:15,547
And I'll tell you something else,
Jack Reed.

753
00:38:15,672 --> 00:38:18,007
I don't think we like the same people
or the same kind of life.

754
00:38:18,091 --> 00:38:20,093
- And I wanna be on my own.
- Go ahead, be on your own!

755
00:38:20,218 --> 00:38:21,761
I don't give a damn!
You're on your own anyway.

756
00:38:21,886 --> 00:38:23,471
Oh! I know you don't give a damn!

757
00:38:23,555 --> 00:38:25,181
Well, will you tell me
why the hell I should give a damn?

758
00:38:25,306 --> 00:38:26,558
You shouldn't! Don't give a damn!

759
00:38:26,683 --> 00:38:29,185
- I don't give a damn, either!
- That's right! I don't give a damn!

760
00:38:29,310 --> 00:38:32,647
- I'm getting out of here!
- Good, fine! I'm leaving, too!

761
00:39:19,694 --> 00:39:23,364
Honey, can we just
get out of New York?

762
00:39:24,616 --> 00:39:26,784
Let's go somewhere
and just write what we wanna write.

763
00:40:00,818 --> 00:40:05,740
Provincetown was
just a tiny little fishing village.

764
00:40:06,157 --> 00:40:09,744
And it was very, very conservative.

765
00:40:10,203 --> 00:40:13,748
We'd take the Fall River steamer
up there, I remember, every summer.

766
00:40:13,831 --> 00:40:16,417
We used to save fares
by sleeping in tiers.

767
00:40:16,501 --> 00:40:18,419
And we always got bedbugs.

768
00:40:18,503 --> 00:40:20,505
You did whatever you pleased up there.

769
00:40:20,588 --> 00:40:24,050
And we put on some very
interesting plays, experimental plays

770
00:40:24,175 --> 00:40:26,594
that a commercial theater
couldn't possibly do.

771
00:40:26,678 --> 00:40:29,514
Take Susan Glaspell's Trifles.

772
00:40:29,681 --> 00:40:31,182
There's a whole play

773
00:40:31,307 --> 00:40:34,686
without the protagonist
even appearing on the stage.

774
00:40:34,811 --> 00:40:37,230
And they gave three one-act plays.

775
00:40:37,480 --> 00:40:39,440
One of them was a play by...

776
00:40:39,524 --> 00:40:43,069
I always thought it was by John Reed
and Louise Bryant.

777
00:40:43,361 --> 00:40:45,029
But I see it's by her.

778
00:40:45,154 --> 00:40:46,155
They were in it.

779
00:40:46,281 --> 00:40:49,075
The play was terrible,
and they were worse.

780
00:40:49,701 --> 00:40:52,662
And of course, Gene O'Neill
was known as the poet,

781
00:40:53,037 --> 00:40:55,957
but I liked his plays
better than his poetry.

782
00:40:56,583 --> 00:40:57,667
Will you never understand?

783
00:40:57,792 --> 00:41:00,378
Are you so stupid
that you do not know what I mean?

784
00:41:00,503 --> 00:41:02,172
I am offering myself to you.

785
00:41:02,255 --> 00:41:04,174
I am kneeling before you.

786
00:41:04,424 --> 00:41:06,509
I have promised you my body,

787
00:41:06,634 --> 00:41:08,845
my body that men have
found so beautiful.

788
00:41:08,970 --> 00:41:12,724
I have promised to love you,
a negro sailor!

789
00:41:13,850 --> 00:41:16,895
Tell them not to stand behind the moon.

790
00:41:17,478 --> 00:41:19,105
Don't stand behind the moon.

791
00:41:19,397 --> 00:41:21,065
- Back?
- Can you step back a little bit?

792
00:41:21,691 --> 00:41:22,817
'Cause of the moon.

793
00:41:22,901 --> 00:41:24,485
This is the moon here.

794
00:41:24,736 --> 00:41:25,987
- This way?
- Yes.

795
00:41:26,237 --> 00:41:28,239
Take it from "I hate the sea."

796
00:41:28,406 --> 00:41:29,490
Will you never understand?

797
00:41:29,574 --> 00:41:31,618
Are you so stupid
that you don't know what I mean?

798
00:41:31,743 --> 00:41:33,453
I'm offering myself to you.

799
00:41:33,578 --> 00:41:35,872
I'm kneeling before you.

800
00:41:35,955 --> 00:41:38,791
I... I, who have had so many men
kneel before me,

801
00:41:38,917 --> 00:41:40,752
I'm offering you my body,

802
00:41:40,877 --> 00:41:43,755
my body that men have
found so beautiful.

803
00:41:44,422 --> 00:41:46,466
I have promised to love you.

804
00:41:46,591 --> 00:41:48,468
You, a negro sailor.

805
00:41:48,593 --> 00:41:52,055
Is that not humiliation enough
that you must keep me waiting so?

806
00:41:52,347 --> 00:41:54,349
Answer me, please! Answer me.

807
00:41:54,474 --> 00:41:56,392
Will you give me that water?

808
00:41:57,852 --> 00:41:59,729
I have no water.

809
00:42:00,563 --> 00:42:02,315
Old Teddy wants this war, doesn't he?

810
00:42:02,440 --> 00:42:04,984
I wonder how long it'll take the public
to find out he's a maniac.

811
00:42:05,109 --> 00:42:07,737
Teddy Roosevelt has rabies.
Universal military training.

812
00:42:07,820 --> 00:42:09,447
Jack, your second speech is out.

813
00:42:09,572 --> 00:42:12,283
And the ironic part of it is
that poor people, they love him.

814
00:42:12,408 --> 00:42:15,245
Sure, they do.
They'll take him up San Juan Hill again.

815
00:42:15,370 --> 00:42:17,205
You can't touch the bunny suit.
It's rented.

816
00:42:17,288 --> 00:42:18,581
Did you read the piece
on the convention?

817
00:42:18,706 --> 00:42:21,084
If the left doesn't defend Wilson,
we're gonna get President Hughes.

818
00:42:21,167 --> 00:42:22,293
Think we ought to go to St. Louis?

819
00:42:22,418 --> 00:42:24,170
I am not going to St. Louis
to defend Wilson.

820
00:42:24,295 --> 00:42:26,256
- I think we should.
- Why? What good would it do?

821
00:42:26,339 --> 00:42:28,216
I don't know,
if you don't think Hughes would have us

822
00:42:28,299 --> 00:42:30,385
in a war in a few months,
it wouldn't do any good at all.

823
00:42:30,468 --> 00:42:32,095
Wilson's kept us out so far.

824
00:42:32,804 --> 00:42:34,514
Reed thought that he was a good poet.

825
00:42:34,639 --> 00:42:36,432
He was a terrible poet.

826
00:42:36,641 --> 00:42:38,893
He thought that he could write
good novels.

827
00:42:38,977 --> 00:42:40,186
Short stories.

828
00:42:40,603 --> 00:42:42,021
Of course, he was a poet.

829
00:42:42,146 --> 00:42:45,608
And not a great poet,

830
00:42:46,025 --> 00:42:48,444
but some of it was very fine.

831
00:42:48,820 --> 00:42:52,699
But, as a journalist,
Jack Reed topped them all.

832
00:42:53,199 --> 00:42:55,243
- Look. Pull this up.
- Hey, Jack.

833
00:42:55,368 --> 00:42:57,120
See? That's good.

834
00:42:57,453 --> 00:42:59,038
Jack, your ride's here.

835
00:42:59,914 --> 00:43:02,625
- Excuse me. I'll wait outside.
- Okay. Okay.

836
00:43:04,169 --> 00:43:07,213
- Do you see what I mean? If one...
- Jack, the taxi's waiting.

837
00:43:11,217 --> 00:43:12,635
Yeah, I got to run.

838
00:43:16,055 --> 00:43:17,098
Bye, honey.

839
00:43:25,190 --> 00:43:27,233
Jack Reed wanted to stir up trouble,

840
00:43:27,358 --> 00:43:29,652
he wanted to stir up trouble
for the capitalists.

841
00:43:29,736 --> 00:43:33,114
And he also wanted
to arouse the working masses

842
00:43:33,364 --> 00:43:36,826
to the necessity of some
kind of effective united action.

843
00:43:37,035 --> 00:43:41,873
In other words, I am accusing him
of either being a busybody

844
00:43:42,123 --> 00:43:45,919
or of being a fraidy-cat,

845
00:43:46,044 --> 00:43:48,254
not wanting to face things
of his own nature.

846
00:43:52,634 --> 00:43:56,095
Dear Louise, St. Louis is very hot
and very crowded with Democrats,

847
00:43:56,221 --> 00:43:59,057
all having a wonderful time
and wearing little paper hats

848
00:43:59,182 --> 00:44:01,017
in anticipation of Wilson's nomination.

849
00:44:01,100 --> 00:44:02,268
I'd like to think it's because

850
00:44:02,393 --> 00:44:04,312
he doesn't want the United States
to go into the war,

851
00:44:04,395 --> 00:44:06,231
but who knows
the mind of a Democrat?

852
00:44:06,356 --> 00:44:09,234
By the way, I've decided to throw out
the poem on white lilies.

853
00:44:09,359 --> 00:44:10,818
The rhyming scheme was wrong.

854
00:44:10,902 --> 00:44:12,987
Maybe when I get back
I can start it again.

855
00:44:13,112 --> 00:44:15,657
Politics sure plays hell
with your poetry.

856
00:44:15,740 --> 00:44:18,535
I keep thinking I see you.
It's the damnedest thing.

857
00:44:18,618 --> 00:44:21,120
I miss you, honey.
I miss walking on the beach.

858
00:45:05,623 --> 00:45:07,709
- Hello.
- Where's the whiskey?

859
00:45:17,135 --> 00:45:18,720
Would you like a glass?

860
00:45:27,854 --> 00:45:29,397
Don't try and decide.

861
00:45:30,148 --> 00:45:31,482
I'll get you one.

862
00:45:36,905 --> 00:45:38,448
I like your play.

863
00:45:38,573 --> 00:45:41,284
I only hope I can do the part justice.

864
00:45:41,993 --> 00:45:44,495
I think your dialogue is beautiful.
I really do, I love it...

865
00:45:44,621 --> 00:45:46,789
Then why the hell
don't you just stand still and say it

866
00:45:46,873 --> 00:45:48,958
instead of wandering all over the stage?

867
00:45:49,083 --> 00:45:51,377
You're supposed to be looking
for your soul, not an ashtray.

868
00:45:51,503 --> 00:45:52,795
Would you rather I didn't smoke
during rehearsals?

869
00:45:52,879 --> 00:45:55,465
I'd rather you went up in flames
than put out your cigarette

870
00:45:55,590 --> 00:45:57,467
in the middle
of a monologue about birth.

871
00:45:57,592 --> 00:45:58,593
I'm sorry. You're absolutely right.

872
00:45:58,676 --> 00:46:00,470
It makes me wanna cancel
the whole production.

873
00:46:00,595 --> 00:46:03,306
I won't do it again.
Excuse me, I'm sorry.

874
00:46:13,191 --> 00:46:15,568
You keep the glass. I'll take the bottle.

875
00:46:16,069 --> 00:46:17,612
Are you leaving?

876
00:46:18,279 --> 00:46:19,739
Give me your glass.

877
00:46:31,125 --> 00:46:32,502
Are you nervous?

878
00:46:33,461 --> 00:46:36,798
- Or is that a tremor?
- Why aren't you in Chicago with Jack?

879
00:46:36,881 --> 00:46:39,634
Why should I be?
He has his things, I have mine.

880
00:46:51,813 --> 00:46:53,898
- What are they?
- What?

881
00:46:57,569 --> 00:47:01,197
The things that you have that are yours.

882
00:47:01,614 --> 00:47:02,824
What are they?

883
00:47:04,951 --> 00:47:06,536
My work, for one.

884
00:47:07,620 --> 00:47:10,206
He's a real mean
son of a bitch, isn't he?

885
00:47:10,915 --> 00:47:12,208
What do you mean?

886
00:47:12,333 --> 00:47:14,627
Leaving you alone with your work.

887
00:47:15,336 --> 00:47:18,089
- You think I mind?
- You should.

888
00:47:19,090 --> 00:47:21,426
It's the one thing
we mustn't be left alone with.

889
00:47:21,551 --> 00:47:24,012
- You may feel that way, I don't.
- Good.

890
00:47:24,137 --> 00:47:28,099
Don't let those village radicals keep you
from being what you should be.

891
00:47:28,641 --> 00:47:30,560
What do you think I should be?

892
00:47:31,227 --> 00:47:33,188
The center of attention.

893
00:47:34,272 --> 00:47:36,816
Well, you must have been
with some very competitive women.

894
00:47:37,609 --> 00:47:39,360
Let's just say possessive.

895
00:47:39,527 --> 00:47:42,197
Possessive? That's something else.

896
00:47:42,447 --> 00:47:43,948
It's a waste of time.

897
00:47:44,657 --> 00:47:45,867
I'm not.

898
00:47:46,951 --> 00:47:49,037
Neither is Jack, for that matter.

899
00:47:49,245 --> 00:47:52,665
Oh, yes. I know.
You and Jack have your own things.

900
00:47:52,790 --> 00:47:55,710
He has the freedom to do the things
that he wants to and so do I.

901
00:47:55,793 --> 00:47:57,795
And I think anyone who's afraid
of that kind of freedom

902
00:47:57,879 --> 00:47:59,923
is really only afraid
of his own emptiness.

903
00:48:01,549 --> 00:48:03,384
Are you making this up
as you go along?

904
00:48:05,303 --> 00:48:06,971
I'd like you to go.

905
00:48:09,557 --> 00:48:10,558
Why?

906
00:48:10,767 --> 00:48:12,101
Because I don't want to be patronized.

907
00:48:12,185 --> 00:48:14,229
I'm sorry if you don't believe
in mutual independence

908
00:48:14,312 --> 00:48:15,605
and free love and respect.

909
00:48:15,730 --> 00:48:19,609
Don't give me a lot of parlor socialism
that you learned in the Village.

910
00:48:20,818 --> 00:48:24,739
If you were mine, I wouldn't share you
with anybody or anything.

911
00:48:25,532 --> 00:48:29,077
It'd be just you and me.
You'd be at the center of it all.

912
00:48:31,746 --> 00:48:33,748
You know,
it would feel lot more like love

913
00:48:33,873 --> 00:48:36,167
than being left alone with your work.

914
00:48:48,513 --> 00:48:52,100
- I hope I haven't upset you.
- Not at all. I'm grateful.

915
00:48:52,684 --> 00:48:55,103
But you seem to be looking
for something much more serious

916
00:48:55,186 --> 00:48:57,146
than what I had in mind.

917
00:48:57,772 --> 00:48:59,858
- Than what you had in mind?
- Yes.

918
00:49:00,859 --> 00:49:04,279
You see, Jack and I
are both perfectly capable

919
00:49:04,404 --> 00:49:06,447
of living with our beliefs.

920
00:49:07,907 --> 00:49:10,827
But I think someone as romantic as you
would be destroyed by them.

921
00:49:11,744 --> 00:49:15,582
And I don't want that to happen.
It would upset Jack too much.

922
00:49:38,062 --> 00:49:40,481
You can't come and play in my yard

923
00:49:41,691 --> 00:49:44,152
I don't love you anymore

924
00:49:45,486 --> 00:49:47,697
You'll be sorry when you see me

925
00:49:48,615 --> 00:49:51,034
Sliding down my cellar door

926
00:49:52,243 --> 00:49:55,371
You can't holler down my rain barrel

927
00:49:55,747 --> 00:49:58,791
You can't climb my apple tree

928
00:50:00,919 --> 00:50:03,421
I don't want to play in your yard

929
00:50:04,255 --> 00:50:06,883
If you can't be good to me

930
00:50:40,959 --> 00:50:43,336
I don't want to play in your yard

931
00:50:43,920 --> 00:50:46,047
I don't like you anymore

932
00:50:46,673 --> 00:50:48,925
You'll be sorry when you see me

933
00:50:49,634 --> 00:50:51,970
Sliding down our cellar door

934
00:50:53,179 --> 00:50:55,765
You can't holler down our rain barrel

935
00:50:56,182 --> 00:50:59,727
You can't climb our apple tree

936
00:51:00,019 --> 00:51:02,981
I don't want to play in your yard

937
00:51:03,481 --> 00:51:06,192
If you won't be good to me

938
00:51:09,571 --> 00:51:10,947
Wonderful!

939
00:51:28,131 --> 00:51:29,465
Floyd, I've been
waiting for this for weeks.

940
00:51:52,488 --> 00:51:54,199
Tap your sensuality.

941
00:52:10,131 --> 00:52:12,175
- Wonderful close.
- Extraordinary.

942
00:52:12,383 --> 00:52:14,177
Very good. Excellent.

943
00:52:16,513 --> 00:52:19,432
- Floyd, that's new for you, isn't it?
- Max, what about you?

944
00:52:19,557 --> 00:52:20,517
- Okay. Who's next?
- I just recited

945
00:52:20,600 --> 00:52:21,893
two-thirds of my new play.

946
00:52:22,018 --> 00:52:24,229
You said it was a work
of uncanny perception.

947
00:52:24,354 --> 00:52:26,981
Oh, did I? How quickly we forget.

948
00:52:44,415 --> 00:52:46,459
- Well!
- Jack. Come in.

949
00:52:47,085 --> 00:52:48,711
News from the front.

950
00:52:48,795 --> 00:52:49,838
- Hello, Jack.
- Hello, Jack.

951
00:52:49,921 --> 00:52:51,422
- Hi, Jack.
- How was the trip?

952
00:52:53,716 --> 00:52:55,134
Welcome back.

953
00:52:55,593 --> 00:52:56,886
- Who's next?
- Nobody's next.

954
00:52:57,762 --> 00:52:59,556
Let's have a dance out of Gene.

955
00:52:59,639 --> 00:53:02,433
Jack, you're just in time
to see O'Neill dance.

956
00:53:03,601 --> 00:53:05,562
Okay. Do something Irish.
Come on, Gene.

957
00:53:05,687 --> 00:53:07,272
Yeah. Let's have it, Gene.

958
00:53:07,397 --> 00:53:09,732
- Yeah. Go ahead Gene.
- Recite something from your new play.

959
00:53:09,816 --> 00:53:11,150
Hutch says it's wonderful.

960
00:53:11,276 --> 00:53:13,778
Tell us about the convention, Jack.
How was Wilson's speech?

961
00:53:13,903 --> 00:53:16,698
Never mind the speech.
What was he wearing?

962
00:53:18,491 --> 00:53:21,619
- What about Wilson?
- Yeah. What about Wilson?

963
00:53:23,454 --> 00:53:26,791
Oh, I don't think there's any reason to
believe that Wilson's gonna do anything

964
00:53:26,916 --> 00:53:30,753
other than support the interest of the
ruling class and take us into the war.

965
00:53:30,837 --> 00:53:34,132
But as long as he says he's against it,
then I think we have to support him.

966
00:53:34,257 --> 00:53:37,385
Because he'll have to make good on
that campaign promise

967
00:53:37,468 --> 00:53:39,512
for at least a few months
and that might give us time

968
00:53:39,637 --> 00:53:41,139
to strengthen the anti-war coalition.

969
00:53:41,264 --> 00:53:44,225
But there's a lot more pro-war feeling in
the streets now than there was before...

970
00:54:00,366 --> 00:54:02,535
You want another drink, Gene?

971
00:54:07,207 --> 00:54:08,583
I guess not.

972
00:54:23,139 --> 00:54:25,308
- Good night.
- Night.

973
00:54:27,060 --> 00:54:28,436
Good night.

974
00:54:39,030 --> 00:54:41,157
Would you like
some cold tea with lemon?

975
