No, thanks.

976
00:54:43,701 --> 00:54:45,495
Well, I'll have some, anyway.

977
00:54:58,716 --> 00:55:01,010
- What's this?
- A poem.

978
00:55:01,886 --> 00:55:03,388
May I read it?

979
00:55:07,392 --> 00:55:09,102
I didn't finish it.

980
00:55:26,202 --> 00:55:27,495
Finish it.

981
00:55:33,793 --> 00:55:35,086
Finish it?

982
00:55:38,965 --> 00:55:42,510
Would that make you happy?
If I were a poet?

983
00:55:45,263 --> 00:55:46,556
I'm happy.

984
00:55:57,108 --> 00:55:59,444
- Jack.
- Why don't you get some sleep?

985
00:56:00,737 --> 00:56:01,821
Jack.

986
00:56:04,407 --> 00:56:06,576
There's something
that I have to tell you.

987
00:56:06,951 --> 00:56:09,704
- You don't have to tell me anything.
- No?

988
00:56:10,788 --> 00:56:11,748
No.

989
00:56:21,299 --> 00:56:23,259
You want to get married?

990
00:56:54,290 --> 00:56:56,042
Okay. There we go. I'll see...

991
00:57:00,213 --> 00:57:03,842
- Oh, careful there. Careful.
- There's two more to come.

992
00:57:04,050 --> 00:57:06,511
Two? No, there should be three.

993
00:57:12,100 --> 00:57:14,519
Oh, excuse me. I'm sorry.
I'm very sorry to hover like this.

994
00:57:14,644 --> 00:57:16,354
It's not that
you're not doing a wonderful job.

995
00:57:16,479 --> 00:57:19,607
It's just that I'm very concerned
about this one particular box.

996
00:57:21,943 --> 00:57:24,028
- Here. No. No.
- I'll take it.

997
00:57:46,426 --> 00:57:48,178
Where's the whiskey?

998
00:57:49,012 --> 00:57:51,973
- Lady, where do you want this?
- Oh, just put it over there.

999
00:57:52,056 --> 00:57:53,850
That'll be fine. Thank you.

1000
00:57:56,394 --> 00:57:57,437
Yeah.

1001
00:57:59,397 --> 00:58:01,691
- Anything to drink in there?
- Drink?

1002
00:58:01,983 --> 00:58:04,777
Oh, here. Thanks.
Thank you very much. I...

1003
00:58:04,903 --> 00:58:07,030
- Thank you. Good.
- Thank you.

1004
00:58:14,454 --> 00:58:19,584
Oh. Well. Let's see now. Here we are.

1005
00:58:22,504 --> 00:58:25,298
- Gene?
- No glass?

1006
00:58:25,423 --> 00:58:27,258
Oh. Let's see.

1007
00:58:28,551 --> 00:58:31,846
Well, I guess I should have
labeled these, shouldn't I have?

1008
00:58:33,515 --> 00:58:35,683
No. No, that isn't the right one.

1009
00:58:36,434 --> 00:58:37,852
Try this one.

1010
00:58:38,895 --> 00:58:41,397
Well, what are you working on, Gene?

1011
00:58:41,898 --> 00:58:43,775
At the moment, Scotch.

1012
00:58:43,942 --> 00:58:46,569
I found a cup. Will a cup be all right?

1013
00:58:46,694 --> 00:58:49,197
- I'd prefer a glass.
- A glass.

1014
00:58:51,241 --> 00:58:55,328
You know,
you left without saying goodbye.

1015
00:58:55,828 --> 00:58:59,624
That's not like you, not that I have
slightest idea what you're like.

1016
00:59:00,166 --> 00:59:02,627
Success at last. See, a... Here we go.

1017
00:59:14,138 --> 00:59:16,933
Your skill as a bartender
seems to have deteriorated.

1018
00:59:17,016 --> 00:59:20,019
- Are you nervous?
- Yes. No. I'm...

1019
00:59:20,270 --> 00:59:24,148
Why should I be nervous? My God,
it's gonna smell like a saloon in here.

1020
00:59:37,120 --> 00:59:41,416
- What is it?
- It's a poem telling you that I love you.

1021
00:59:42,417 --> 00:59:45,628
And that I won't be possessive
and I won't be jealous.

1022
00:59:45,753 --> 00:59:49,716
And you can sleep with whoever
you want, live with whoever you want.

1023
00:59:50,008 --> 00:59:54,095
I'll do anything that you say.
I'd like to kill you, but I can't.

1024
00:59:55,972 --> 00:59:58,433
So you can do whatever you want to,

1025
00:59:59,726 --> 01:00:01,352
except not see me.

1026
01:00:03,813 --> 01:00:06,441
Or smoke during the monologue.

1027
01:00:10,945 --> 01:00:13,865
Gene, Jack and I,
we haven't told anyone yet

1028
01:00:13,990 --> 01:00:16,284
because we were too embarrassed.

1029
01:00:17,327 --> 01:00:18,453
But

1030
01:00:20,205 --> 01:00:21,664
we're married.

1031
01:00:22,123 --> 01:00:24,042
Jack and I got married.

1032
01:00:27,712 --> 01:00:31,216
- That is embarrassing.
- Yes. Isn't it?

1033
01:00:31,341 --> 01:00:33,843
We felt very silly, but we wanted to do it.

1034
01:00:33,968 --> 01:00:36,179
And it's gonna be good.
We're gonna work together.

1035
01:00:36,262 --> 01:00:38,014
We're gonna spend
all our time together.

1036
01:00:38,097 --> 01:00:39,766
That's why we took a lease
on this place,

1037
01:00:39,891 --> 01:00:41,476
so we wouldn't have to go back
to the city.

1038
01:00:41,559 --> 01:00:42,894
Does this mean that we have to cheat?

1039
01:00:43,019 --> 01:00:44,979
Or is this a free
and independent marriage?

1040
01:00:45,063 --> 01:00:47,398
- Gene.
- You're a lying Irish whore from Portland

1041
01:00:47,524 --> 01:00:50,235
and you used me
to get Jack Reed to marry you.

1042
01:00:50,735 --> 01:00:52,153
No, I didn't.

1043
01:00:52,904 --> 01:00:54,989
I just want us to be friends, Gene.

1044
01:00:55,073 --> 01:00:57,825
Oh, how genteel. That would be a
good role for you, wouldn't it?

1045
01:00:57,909 --> 01:01:00,411
"There's Louise with Jack and Gene.

1046
01:01:00,912 --> 01:01:03,498
"He's crazy about her,
but Jack doesn't know.

1047
01:01:03,581 --> 01:01:08,211
"Poor Jack. Poor Gene.
What a heartbreaker she is."

1048
01:01:13,466 --> 01:01:15,969
What a heartbreaker you are, Louise.

1049
01:01:17,428 --> 01:01:19,013
I'm sorry. I'm...

1050
01:01:21,516 --> 01:01:22,892
Where is he?

1051
01:01:25,436 --> 01:01:26,771
Washington.

1052
01:01:26,938 --> 01:01:28,565
Well, Mrs. Reed,

1053
01:01:29,732 --> 01:01:33,403
I'll do whatever you say.
What do you want me to do?

1054
01:01:35,655 --> 01:01:37,115
Wish us well?

1055
01:01:49,043 --> 01:01:50,587
I wish you well.

1056
01:01:52,714 --> 01:01:54,132
You and Jack.

1057
01:02:32,170 --> 01:02:33,213
Jack!

1058
01:02:35,131 --> 01:02:36,299
Oh, God.

1059
01:02:39,385 --> 01:02:42,055
I'm not sure whether she had an affair

1060
01:02:42,680 --> 01:02:45,350
with Eugene O'Neill or not
during this time.

1061
01:02:45,934 --> 01:02:48,228
And nobody seemed to know. Or...

1062
01:02:48,686 --> 01:02:51,314
It was nobody's business, anyway, so...

1063
01:02:52,190 --> 01:02:54,651
I don't know what that situation was.

1064
01:02:54,859 --> 01:02:58,321
The report was that
she and Reed and O'Neill

1065
01:02:58,446 --> 01:03:00,615
had a mnage  trois.

1066
01:03:03,868 --> 01:03:06,996
Jack, what... What is...

1067
01:03:22,095 --> 01:03:23,805
Oh, God! I swear...

1068
01:03:24,222 --> 01:03:27,100
...that we love America!

1069
01:03:27,892 --> 01:03:30,728
We love her mountains, her forests...

1070
01:03:30,854 --> 01:03:33,106
There were mutinies
in the French army,

1071
01:03:33,231 --> 01:03:36,109
there were mutinies
in various parts of the front.

1072
01:03:36,234 --> 01:03:40,280
And then, in 1917, the troops,
poorly armed,

1073
01:03:40,780 --> 01:03:43,950
poorly equipped, poorly clothed,
went back to Russia

1074
01:03:44,158 --> 01:03:45,451
to talk it out with the czar.

1075
01:03:45,577 --> 01:03:47,203
And when they got through,
there wasn't any czar.

1076
01:03:47,453 --> 01:03:49,205
Revolution in Russia.

1077
01:03:49,539 --> 01:03:52,417
This was the spring of 1917.

1078
01:03:53,334 --> 01:03:55,211
And I became so excited

1079
01:03:55,670 --> 01:03:59,174
that I zigzag-jumped the benches

1080
01:03:59,841 --> 01:04:02,010
as we walked out of the park.

1081
01:04:02,177 --> 01:04:04,888
Oh, I was so happy as a young boy.

1082
01:04:04,971 --> 01:04:07,348
Revolution, the people take over,

1083
01:04:08,224 --> 01:04:09,559
down with the czar!

1084
01:04:11,519 --> 01:04:12,687
Naturally, I was happy.

1085
01:04:55,980 --> 01:04:58,983
Well, haven't you made the politics
a little nebulous here?

1086
01:04:59,108 --> 01:05:01,027
- What do you mean "nebulous"?
- Unclear...

1087
01:05:01,152 --> 01:05:03,988
- How can you say they're unclear?
- Well, they're unclear to me. I...

1088
01:05:04,113 --> 01:05:05,365
Why am I necessarily attempting

1089
01:05:05,490 --> 01:05:07,659
to define the politics
of a specific group of people?

1090
01:05:07,784 --> 01:05:11,162
It isn't what I said.
I think it's a vast oversimplification.

1091
01:05:13,289 --> 01:05:15,291
Oh, it's just an opinion.

1092
01:05:18,837 --> 01:05:21,339
You know,
if you made carbons of these,

1093
01:05:21,422 --> 01:05:23,550
I could take them on the train with me.

1094
01:05:24,008 --> 01:05:26,469
Wilson, of course,
was elected on the platform of

1095
01:05:26,553 --> 01:05:29,180
"Keep us out of war" in 1916.

1096
01:05:29,681 --> 01:05:33,518
But in 1917, Wilson reversed himself

1097
01:05:33,893 --> 01:05:37,146
and declared war against Germany.

1098
01:05:37,313 --> 01:05:40,650
The mission at that time was to make
the world safe for democracy.

1099
01:05:41,359 --> 01:05:42,652
Reed said,

1100
01:05:44,195 --> 01:05:48,908
"This is a war for democracy?
Where is the goddamn democracy?"

1101
01:05:49,534 --> 01:05:54,330
If men really disapproved of war, dear,
we'd have stopped wars years ago.

1102
01:05:55,748 --> 01:05:57,917
Men like wars. Always have.

1103
01:05:59,460 --> 01:06:02,505
So they all went and got little uniforms,
went to war.

1104
01:06:03,006 --> 01:06:05,466
- My country is at war!
- Yes.

1105
01:06:05,717 --> 01:06:09,596
And so today, I, too, am at war!

1106
01:06:11,681 --> 01:06:14,475
My name is Jack Reed,
I'm from New York.

1107
01:06:14,851 --> 01:06:17,770
This is not my war, and I'm not gonna
have anything to do with it!

1108
01:06:18,021 --> 01:06:19,397
All right. All right.

1109
01:06:19,898 --> 01:06:20,940
All right, folks.

1110
01:06:21,065 --> 01:06:23,568
There was a lot of anti-war feeling,
of course.

1111
01:06:23,651 --> 01:06:27,113
We had no one against the war.
There wasn't a soul against the war.

1112
01:06:27,822 --> 01:06:31,743
Well, I'm not talking about saying it
to the workers any other way.

1113
01:06:32,327 --> 01:06:34,871
How do we move them?

1114
01:06:34,996 --> 01:06:36,915
Right. How do we organize them?

1115
01:06:37,040 --> 01:06:39,209
The Socialist Party...

1116
01:06:42,795 --> 01:06:45,048
The Socialist Party of America
is nothing to sneeze at.

1117
01:06:45,131 --> 01:06:47,884
You think the Socialist Party
is going to take a position?

1118
01:06:47,967 --> 01:06:49,469
You boys are Reds, aren't you?

1119
01:06:49,594 --> 01:06:53,223
The Socialist Party is useless.
Jack, is that right?

1120
01:06:53,431 --> 01:06:55,558
Now, that's the truth. Jack?

1121
01:06:55,975 --> 01:06:57,060
The United States is at war.

1122
01:06:57,143 --> 01:06:58,895
Your friends are talking to you.

1123
01:06:59,020 --> 01:07:02,440
If the workers of the world act together,
they can stop the war. And I'm not...

1124
01:07:02,524 --> 01:07:04,234
This one even pisses red.

1125
01:07:06,236 --> 01:07:08,821
You ran around saving the world
until your kidney acted up again.

1126
01:07:08,947 --> 01:07:10,114
Very intelligent.

1127
01:07:10,240 --> 01:07:12,158
And you're gonna keep running around
making speeches

1128
01:07:12,283 --> 01:07:13,993
until you wind up
in the hospital. Brilliant.

1129
01:07:14,118 --> 01:07:15,912
And then,
you're gonna lose your kidney. Perfect.

1130
01:07:15,995 --> 01:07:18,289
Harry, how much is the government
paying you to keep me quiet?

1131
01:07:18,414 --> 01:07:19,624
- Very funny. Keep laughing.
- Yeah.

1132
01:07:19,749 --> 01:07:21,918
That hurt, didn't it?

1133
01:07:23,127 --> 01:07:25,129
Listen, I'm gonna tell you something.

1134
01:07:25,255 --> 01:07:27,924
You're not gonna be able to keep doing
what you've been doing.

1135
01:07:28,049 --> 01:07:29,968
This is a serious condition.
It could kill you.

1136
01:07:30,093 --> 01:07:33,429
Harry, look, I want to know if...

1137
01:07:34,222 --> 01:07:37,016
Could this thing interfere
with having children?

1138
01:07:37,141 --> 01:07:41,020
- Yes. You cannot have sex if you die.
- No, come on, Harry. Seriously.

1139
01:07:42,188 --> 01:07:44,858
Are you thinking about having children?

1140
01:07:45,608 --> 01:07:48,570
Not at the moment,
but I want to be able to...

1141
01:07:50,738 --> 01:07:52,782
Is Louise talking about it?

1142
01:07:53,992 --> 01:07:54,993
No.

1143
01:07:55,368 --> 01:07:57,245
Well, just because
she isn't talking about it

1144
01:07:57,328 --> 01:07:58,913
it doesn't mean
she isn't thinking about it.

1145
01:07:58,997 --> 01:08:01,291
Don't worry. You don't make babies
with your kidneys.

1146
01:08:01,374 --> 01:08:03,126
Look, I'm gonna send you home
to Louise.

1147
01:08:03,251 --> 01:08:04,919
Tell her to keep you there,
put you in bed,

1148
01:08:05,003 --> 01:08:07,463
give you lots of liquids.
I'm gonna write it all down.

1149
01:08:07,964 --> 01:08:10,925
Look, Louise doesn't know about
this. And I don't want her to, okay?

1150
01:08:11,050 --> 01:08:12,760
- Fine.
- So, can you give me my bill here?

1151
01:08:12,844 --> 01:08:15,638
- I don't want it sent to the house.
- Do you have any money?

1152
01:08:19,517 --> 01:08:20,560
Not at the moment.

1153
01:08:20,727 --> 01:08:23,146
Then why the hell
should I give you a bill? Go home.

1154
01:08:23,479 --> 01:08:26,983
It is my belief that socialism and peace
are inseparable.

1155
01:08:27,192 --> 01:08:31,029
And I reiterate that the Socialist Party
will stand firmly behind

1156
01:08:31,154 --> 01:08:34,407
its resolution to oppose
American involvement in this war!

1157
01:08:34,532 --> 01:08:36,868
Mr. Chairman, Louis Fraina,
Local Boston.

1158
01:08:36,993 --> 01:08:39,537
The chair recognizes
the delegate from Boston.

1159
01:08:39,662 --> 01:08:40,663
And I still want to know

1160
01:08:40,788 --> 01:08:43,583
what specific action
we are going to take against the war.

1161
01:08:43,708 --> 01:08:45,210
Your resolution is all very nice,

1162
01:08:45,335 --> 01:08:48,171
but will it stop even one boy from
being killed? I don't think so.

1163
01:08:48,254 --> 01:08:50,507
...stigmatized as unpatriotic.

1164
01:08:50,798 --> 01:08:52,884
The task that confronts us is difficult.

1165
01:08:53,009 --> 01:08:54,761
Let us hope
that we can handle it properly.

1166
01:08:54,886 --> 01:08:56,012
What's that supposed to mean?

1167
01:08:56,095 --> 01:08:57,263
Stupid!

1168
01:08:57,722 --> 01:09:01,601
I'd like to know if the Socialist Party
is gonna fight conscription or not.

1169
01:09:01,726 --> 01:09:04,562
- That's what I'd like to know.
- Will the delegate identify himself?

1170
01:09:04,687 --> 01:09:07,148
I am not a delegate, Mr. Chairman.
My name is John Reed,

1171
01:09:07,273 --> 01:09:08,733
I write for the magazine The Masses,

1172
01:09:08,816 --> 01:09:11,861
and I want to know if the Socialist Party
is gonna organize demonstrations...

1173
01:09:11,945 --> 01:09:14,030
I'm sorry, Mr. Reed.
You have no credentials here.

1174
01:09:14,113 --> 01:09:17,200
Now, this floor is reserved
for delegates, not journalists.

1175
01:09:17,283 --> 01:09:19,035
Mr. Chairman,
is the Socialist Party prepared

1176
01:09:19,118 --> 01:09:20,787
- to take a position on the draft or not?
- Hey, shut up!

1177
01:09:20,912 --> 01:09:23,206
I'm sorry, Mr. Reed.
You have no credentials.

1178
01:09:23,289 --> 01:09:24,415
Let him speak, will you?

1179
01:09:24,541 --> 01:09:26,960
Mr. Reed,
you're getting into party politics, eh?

1180
01:09:27,085 --> 01:09:29,379
I'm just trying to be a journalist.
Mr. Chairman...

1181
01:09:29,462 --> 01:09:32,632
So is Trotsky.
Let us see what happens in Russia.

1182
01:09:32,757 --> 01:09:36,427
Why don't you join the Socialist Party?
We need good people like you.

1183
01:09:36,553 --> 01:09:38,555
Big things are happening in Russia.

1184
01:09:38,680 --> 01:09:42,100
As appalling as it may seem
to see socialists supporting bloodshed,

1185
01:09:42,225 --> 01:09:44,727
I can understand the necessity
of supporting one's government

1186
01:09:44,853 --> 01:09:46,145
during times of war.

1187
01:09:46,271 --> 01:09:49,023
The task that confronts us is a giant!

1188
01:09:49,440 --> 01:09:52,527
In that,
we must continue our opposition!

1189
01:10:06,416 --> 01:10:09,836
- We have to give this dog a name.
- Well, she has a name.

1190
01:10:10,753 --> 01:10:12,589
What's the matter with her name?

1191
01:10:13,047 --> 01:10:16,259
- I can't find anything in this house.
- I'm not going to call a dog "Dog."

1192
01:10:16,342 --> 01:10:18,595
I suppose if she were a baby,
you'd wanna call her "Person."

1193
01:10:18,720 --> 01:10:20,597
Not really.
I think I might wanna call her "Jack."

1194
01:10:20,680 --> 01:10:22,098
No. No. Bad.

1195
01:10:22,182 --> 01:10:23,766
See, now this is why
I can't find anything.

1196
01:10:23,892 --> 01:10:24,934
You put things anywhere.

1197
01:10:25,059 --> 01:10:26,477
Dog! Dog!

1198
01:10:26,644 --> 01:10:28,479
She's still not housebroken.

1199
01:10:28,605 --> 01:10:30,982
You got to grab her
when she squats like that,

1200
01:10:31,107 --> 01:10:33,735
and then take her outside. That's right.

1201
01:10:33,818 --> 01:10:36,613
And then when she goes,
you've got to give her a reward.

1202
01:10:36,821 --> 01:10:38,615
All right. Now, stay, Dog.

1203
01:10:38,698 --> 01:10:40,700
Are we having garlic for dinner, honey?

1204
01:10:40,825 --> 01:10:41,826
No, no, no.

1205
01:10:49,709 --> 01:10:52,795
Why? Why, do you think
I'm using too much garlic?

1206
01:10:53,505 --> 01:10:55,924
I thought I'd put a little in the sauce.

1207
01:10:56,007 --> 01:10:58,009
Garlic doesn't bother me.

1208
01:11:10,021 --> 01:11:13,566
- That's from Gene.
- Sorry. I didn't mean to read it.

1209
01:11:14,484 --> 01:11:16,236
I didn't realize what it was.

1210
01:11:23,535 --> 01:11:26,746
He gave it to me in October.
